<div class="comment-wrapper"><ul class="comments"><li class="comment"><div class="avatar"><img src="https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/06c1dcc7dce6a93d194b9c013376e3f0?s=50"></div><header><strong>Combining native and ObjC swift_class_getInstanceExtents entry points</strong> from <string>Joe Groff</string> &lt;jgroff at apple.com&gt;<p>December 23, 2015 at 04:00:00pm</p></header><div class="content"><p>In the runtime currently, there are two entry points for asking for the size of a class&#39;s instances, one for known-native Swift classes, and one for possibly-ObjC classes. It looks like they&#39;re only currently used for _debugPrecondition checks in ManagedBuffer&#39;s initializers to catch improperly-sized subclasses in debug builds, so I&#39;m wondering whether saving an `isObjC` branch in the known-native case is worth the extra entry point. Any concerns with merging them?<br></p><p>-Joe<br></p></div></li></ul></div>    </main>
